{
  "text": "We used the peptides derived from syntaxin to examine whether the interaction between syntaxin and VAMP or a-SNAP is involved in axonal growth. The domain of syntaxin that is responsible for the interaction with other proteins has been determined in detail [CITATION_1] . Based on this data, we designed peptides 1 and 2 to include one of the critical portions for its interaction with VAMP, and with both VAMP and a-SNAP [CITATION_2] . According to [CITATION_3] , mutated peptides The effect of these peptides on neurite outgrowth using the trituration method for introducing these peptides into the dissociated rat DRG neurons. The peptides used are as follows: peptide 1 (AVDYVERAVS, amino acid numbers from 240 to 249 of rat syntaxin la) [CITATION_4] , and peptide lm (VVDAERAVS); peptide 2 (VESQGEMIDR; amino acid numbers from 223 to 232 of rat syntaxin la), and peptide 2m (AESAGEMIDR). The underline shows the amino acid substitution for the original ones. Data shown are the average and SEM of four independent experiments. **, P < 0.01 (vs the PBS-treated group). lm and 2m, for which two positions of specific amino acids are substituted, lose the activity to interact with such proteins. These peptides were effectively introduced into growth cones and dissociated neurons using SLO permeabilization [CITATION_5] or trituration [CITATION_6] methods. Peptide 2 was stronger in both growth cone collapse and neurite outgrowth inhibition than peptide 1 (see Results and Fig. 10) . Considering the parallelism between the biological activity to inhibit the growth cone and the proposed activity to interact with VAMP or with a-SNAP (Fig. 10) , we concluded that the peptides interfere with the regulation of the SNARE complex in the growth cone.",
  "correct_citation": {
